See Power management/Suspend and hibernate#Changing suspend method for the general context in which this workaround applies.

The firmware does not expose the necessary ACPI object (\_S3) to support suspend-to-RAM, but it does have a similarly named object (\XS3), which is most likely patched at boot-time to enable this functionality (although there is no UEFI option to configure this). One can manually add support for suspend-to-RAM by doing the following:

First, get the iasl compiler by installing the acpica package.

Then compile the following source using iasl <file>.asl:

```
DefinitionBlock ("ssdt.aml", "SSDT", 1, "HACK  ", "S3      ", 0x00000001)
{
	Scope (\)
	{
		Name (_S3, Package (0x04)
		{
			0x03,
			Zero,
			Zero,
			Zero
		})
	}
}
```

And finally, tell the kernel to use the new ACPI table.
